nd, United Kingdom":"Rackheath, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Rackneath, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","West Horsley, Surrey, England":"West Horsley, Surrey, England","Morley, Yorkshire, England":"Morley, Yorkshire, England","Morley, Norfolk, England":"Morley St Peter, Norfolk, England","Swanton Morley,,Norfolk,England":"Swanton Morley, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Morley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Morley (for example in Derbyshire, County Durham, Norfolk, and Yorkshire), or Moreleigh in Devon, all of which are named from Old English <i>mōr</i> ‘moor’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Irish (Mayo): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Murghaile</b> ‘descendant of <i>Murghal</i>’, a personal name based on <i>muir</i> ‘sea’ + <i>gal</i> ‘valour’.","Irish (Mayo): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Murthuile</b> ‘descendant of <i>Murthuile</i>’, a personal name derived from <i>muir</i> ‘sea’ + <i>tuile</i> ‘tide’."],"variants":[{"name":"Marler","meanings":["occupational name from Middle English <i>marler</i>, either ‘spreader of marl (as fertilizer)’ or ‘hewer or quarrier of marl’.","topographic name from Middle English <i>marlere</i> ‘marl-pit’ (Old French <i>marliere</i>).","in Norfolk, perhaps also a variant of   Morley  ."]},{"name":"Murley","meanings":["Irish (Cork and Kerry): variant of   Morley  .","English (Cornwall and Somerset): habitational name from Murley in Uplowman (Devon). The placename derives from Old English <i>mōr</i> ‘moor’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. There may well have been some confusion with   Morley  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Morley was born in 1390, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Thomas Morley, was 15 and his mother, Isabel Moleyns, was 16. He married Mrs William Morley in 1415, in Swanton Morley, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1416, in his hometown, at the age of 26."},"et":{"1390–1416":"1390–1416","1394–1435":"1394–1435","1395–Male":"1395–Surnud","1390–Female":"1390–Surnud","1416–1504":"1416–1504","1375–1401":"1375–1401","1374–1408":"1374–1408","1374":"1374","1395":"1395","1394":"1394","1390":"1390","8/1393":"august 1393","1415":"1415","1435":"1435","1401":"1401","Oct 1401":"oktoober 1401","1375":"1375","1408":"1408","1416":"1416","1504":"1504","Rackheath, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Rackheath, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rackneath, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","West Horsley, Surrey, England":"West Horsley, Surrey, England","Morley, Yorkshire, England":"Morley, Yorkshire, England","Morley, Norfolk, England":"Morley St Peter, Norfolk, England","Swanton Morley,,Norfolk,England":"Swanton Morley, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1390–1416":"1390–1416","1394–1435":"1394–1435","1395–Male":"1395–Kuollut","1390–Female":"1390–Kuollut","1416–1504":"1416–1504","1375–1401":"1375–1401","1374–1408":"1374–1408","1374":"1374","1395":"1395","1394":"1394","1390":"1390","8/1393":"elokuu 1393","1415":"1415","1435":"1435","14